xuality, and ethnicity. Rooted in the Foucauldian premise that the history of space is essentially the history of power, and supported by Susan Stanford Friedman's cultural geographies of encounter as well as Gloria Anzaldúa's study of borderlands, this study shows that, by rejecting traditional spatial hierarchies, Allende's trilogy systematically deterritorializes the elite while shifting the previously marginalized to the physical and thematic centers of her works. This movement provides the narrative energy which draws the reader into Allende's universe, and sustains the 'good story' for which she has been universally acclaimed. KAREN WOOLEY MARTIN is Associate Professor of Spanish at Union University, Jackson, Tennessee.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aHispanic Studies. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aFamily Saga.  aHouse of the Spirits.  aIdentity.  aIsabel Allende.  aLocations.  aLove.  aMagical Realism.  aNarrative Geographies.  aPolitical Turmoil.  aSocial Class.  aSouth America.  aStrong Female Characters.  aTrilogy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846158117?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158117/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles